# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dkim-signing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:dkim-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] A **digital signature** is a mathematical scheme for verifying the authenticity of digital messages or documents.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] A valid digital signature on a message gives a recipient confidence that the message came from a sender known to the recipient.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures are a type of public-key cryptography, and are commonly used for software distribution, financial transactions, contract management software, and in other cases where it is important to detect forgery or tampering.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures are often used to implement electronic signatures, which include any electronic data that carries the intent of a signature, but not all electronic signatures use digital signatures.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] *Security* (existential unforgeability under chosen-message attack, or EUF-CMA): It should be computationally infeasible to generate a valid signature for a party without knowing that party's private key.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Here 1*n* refers to a unary number in the formalism of computational complexity theory.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] where *A**S*(*sk*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle, *S*(*sk*, · ), *Q* denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows the public key, *pk*, and the security parameter, *n*, and *x* ∉ *Q* denotes that the adversary may not directly query the string, *x*, on *S*.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman first described the notion of a digital signature scheme, although they only conjectured that such schemes existed based on functions that are trapdoor one-way permutations.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Soon afterwards, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman invented the RSA algorithm, which could be used to produce primitive digital signatures (although only as a proof-of-concept – "plain" RSA signatures are not secure).
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The first widely marketed software package to offer digital signature was Lotus Notes 1.0, released in 1989, which used the RSA algorithm.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Other digital signature schemes were soon developed after RSA, the earliest being Lamport signatures, Merkle signatures (also known as "Merkle trees" or simply "Hash trees"), and Rabin signatures.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In 1988, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Ronald Rivest became the first to rigorously define the security requirements of digital signature schemes.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] They described a hierarchy of attack models for signature schemes, and also presented the GMR signature scheme, the first that could be proved to prevent even an existential forgery against a chosen message attack, which is the currently accepted security definition for signature schemes.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The first such scheme which is not built on trapdoor functions but rather on a family of function with a much weaker required property of one-way permutation was presented by Moni Naor and Moti Yung.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] One digital signature scheme (of many) is based on RSA.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] To create signature keys, generate an RSA key pair containing a modulus, *N*, that is the product of two random secret distinct large primes, along with integers, *e* and *d*, such that *e* *d* ≡ 1 (mod *φ*(*N*)), where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The signer's public key consists of *N* and *e*, and the signer's secret key contains *d*.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Used directly, this type of signature scheme is vulnerable to key-only existential forgery attack.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] To create a forgery, the attacker picks a random signature σ and uses the verification procedure to determine the message, *m*, corresponding to that signature.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In practice, however, this type of signature is not used directly, but rather, the message to be signed is first hashed to produce a short digest, that is then padded to larger width comparable to *N*, then signed with the reverse trapdoor function.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] This forgery attack, then, only produces the padded hash function output that corresponds to σ, but not a message that leads to that value, which does not lead to an attack.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In the random oracle model, hash-then-sign (an idealized version of that practice where hash and padding combined have close to *N* possible outputs), this form of signature is existentially unforgeable, even against a chosen-plaintext attack.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] There are several reasons to sign such a hash (or message digest) instead of the whole document.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The signature will be much shorter and thus save time since hashing is generally much faster than signing in practice.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] A hash function can be used to convert an arbitrary input into the proper format.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Without the hash function, the text "to be signed" may have to be split (separated) in blocks small enough for the signature scheme to act on them directly.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] However, the receiver of the signed blocks is not able to recognize if all the blocks are present and in the appropriate order.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] As organizations move away from paper documents with ink signatures or authenticity stamps, digital signatures can provide added assurances of the evidence to provenance, identity, and status of an electronic document as well as acknowledging informed consent and approval by a signatory.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The United States Government Printing Office (GPO) publishes electronic versions of the budget, public and private laws, and congressional bills with digital signatures.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Universities including Penn State, University of Chicago, and Stanford are publishing electronic student transcripts with digital signatures.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] A message may have letterhead or a handwritten signature identifying its sender, but letterheads and handwritten signatures can be copied and pasted onto forged messages.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Even legitimate messages may be modified in transit.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] With a digital signature scheme, the central office can arrange beforehand to have a public key on file whose private key is known only to the branch office.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The branch office can later sign a message and the central office can use the public key to verify the signed message was not a forgery before acting on it.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] A forger who *doesn't* know the sender's private key can't sign a different message, or even change a single digit in an existing message without making the recipient's signature verification fail.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Non-repudiation, or more specifically non-repudiation of origin, is an important aspect of digital signatures.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] By this property, an entity that has signed some information cannot at a later time deny having signed it.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Similarly, access to the public key only does not enable a fraudulent party to fake a valid signature.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Note that these authentication, non-repudiation etc. properties rely on the secret key *not having been revoked* prior to its usage.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Public revocation of a key-pair is a required ability, else leaked secret keys would continue to implicate the claimed owner of the key-pair.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Checking revocation status requires an "online" check; e.g., checking a certificate revocation list or via the Online Certificate Status Protocol.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Very roughly this is analogous to a vendor who receives credit-cards first checking online with the credit-card issuer to find if a given card has been reported lost or stolen.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Of course, with stolen key pairs, the theft is often discovered only after the secret key's use, e.g., to sign a bogus certificate for espionage purpose.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In a *known message* attack, the attacker is given valid signatures for a variety of messages known by the attacker but not chosen by the attacker.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In an *adaptive chosen message* attack, the attacker first learns signatures on arbitrary messages of the attacker's choice.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] A universal forgery attack results in the ability to forge signatures for any message.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] A selective forgery attack results in a signature on a message of the adversary's choice.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] An existential forgery merely results in some valid message/signature pair not already known to the adversary.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The strongest notion of security, therefore, is security against existential forgery under an adaptive chosen message attack.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] All public key / private key cryptosystems depend entirely on keeping the private key secret.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] A more secure alternative is to store the private key on a smart card.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Many smart cards are designed to be tamper-resistant (although some designs have been broken, notably by Ross Anderson and his students).
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In a typical digital signature implementation, the hash calculated from the document is sent to the smart card, whose CPU signs the hash using the stored private key of the user, and then returns the signed hash.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Typically, a user must activate their smart card by entering a personal identification number or PIN code (thus providing two-factor authentication).
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] It can be arranged that the private key never leaves the smart card, although this is not always implemented.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] If the smart card is stolen, the thief will still need the PIN code to generate a digital signature.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] This reduces the security of the scheme to that of the PIN system, although it still requires an attacker to possess the card.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] A mitigating factor is that private keys, if generated and stored on smart cards, are usually regarded as difficult to copy, and are assumed to exist in exactly one copy.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Thus, the loss of the smart card may be detected by the owner and the corresponding certificate can be immediately revoked.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Private keys that are protected by software only may be easier to copy, and such compromises are far more difficult to detect.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Entering a PIN code to activate the smart card commonly requires a numeric keypad.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Some card readers have their own numeric keypad.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] This is safer than using a card reader integrated into a PC, and then entering the PIN using that computer's keyboard.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Readers with a numeric keypad are meant to circumvent the eavesdropping threat where the computer might be running a keystroke logger, potentially compromising the PIN code.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Specialized card readers are also less vulnerable to tampering with their software or hardware and are often EAL3 certified.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Smart card design is an active field, and there are smart card schemes which are intended to avoid these particular problems, despite having few security proofs so far.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a digital signature and a written signature is that the user does not "see" what they sign.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The user application presents a hash code to be signed by the digital signing algorithm using the private key.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] An attacker who gains control of the user's PC can possibly replace the user application with a foreign substitute, in effect replacing the user's own communications with those of the attacker.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] This could allow a malicious application to trick a user into signing any document by displaying the user's original on-screen, but presenting the attacker's own documents to the signing application.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] To protect against this scenario, an authentication system can be set up between the user's application (word processor, email client, etc.) and the signing application.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The general idea is to provide some means for both the user application and signing application to verify each other's integrity.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] For example, the signing application may require all requests to come from digitally signed binaries.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a cloud based digital signature service and a locally provided one is risk.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Many risk averse companies, including governments, financial and medical institutions, and payment processors require more secure standards, like FIPS 140-2 level 3 and FIPS 201 certification, to ensure the signature is validated and secure.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Technically speaking, a digital signature applies to a string of bits, whereas humans and applications "believe" that they sign the semantic interpretation of those bits.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In order to be semantically interpreted, the bit string must be transformed into a form that is meaningful for humans and applications, and this is done through a combination of hardware and software based processes on a computer system.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The problem is that the semantic interpretation of bits can change as a function of the processes used to transform the bits into semantic content.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] It is relatively easy to change the interpretation of a digital document by implementing changes on the computer system where the document is being processed.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] From a semantic perspective this creates uncertainty about what exactly has been signed.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] WYSIWYS (What You See Is What You Sign) means that the semantic interpretation of a signed message cannot be changed.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In particular this also means that a message cannot contain hidden information that the signer is unaware of, and that can be revealed after the signature has been applied.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] WYSIWYS is a requirement for the validity of digital signatures, but this requirement is difficult to guarantee because of the increasing complexity of modern computer systems.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The term WYSIWYS was coined by Peter Landrock and Torben Pedersen to describe some of the principles in delivering secure and legally binding digital signatures for Pan-European projects.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures cryptographically bind an electronic identity to an electronic document and the digital signature cannot be copied to another document.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Paper contracts sometimes have the ink signature block on the last page, and the previous pages may be replaced after a signature is applied.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures can be applied to an entire document, such that the digital signature on the last page will indicate tampering if any data on any of the pages have been altered, but this can also be achieved by signing with ink and numbering all pages of the contract.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Quality implementations: An implementation of a good algorithm (or protocol) with mistake(s) will not work.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Users (and their software) must carry out the signature protocol properly.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The private key must remain private: If the private key becomes known to any other party, that party can produce *perfect* digital signatures of anything.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The public key owner must be verifiable: A public key associated with Bob actually came from Bob.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] This is commonly done using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and the public key↔user association is attested by the operator of the PKI (called a certificate authority).
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] For 'open' PKIs in which anyone can request such an attestation (universally embodied in a cryptographically protected public key certificate), the possibility of mistaken attestation is non-trivial.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Commercial PKI operators have suffered several publicly known problems.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Such mistakes could lead to falsely signed, and thus wrongly attributed, documents.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] 'Closed' PKI systems are more expensive, but less easily subverted in this way.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Only if all of these conditions are met will a digital signature actually be any evidence of who sent the message, and therefore of their assent to its contents.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Legal enactment cannot change this reality of the existing engineering possibilities, though some such have not reflected this actuality.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] The first appears to have been in Utah in the United States, followed closely by the states Massachusetts and California.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Other countries have also passed statutes or issued regulations in this area as well and the UN has had an active model law project for some time.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Adoption of technical standards for digital signatures have lagged behind much of the legislation, delaying a more or less unified engineering position on interoperability, algorithm choice, key lengths, and so on what the engineering is attempting to provide.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Some industries have established common interoperability standards for the use of digital signatures between members of the industry and with regulators.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] These include the Automotive Network Exchange for the automobile industry and the SAFE-BioPharma Association for the healthcare industry.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] In several countries, a digital signature has a status somewhat like that of a traditional pen and paper signature, as in the 1999 EU digital signature directive and 2014 EU follow-on legislation.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Generally, these provisions mean that anything digitally signed legally binds the signer of the document to the terms therein.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] For that reason, it is often thought best to use separate key pairs for encrypting and signing.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Using the encryption key pair, a person can engage in an encrypted conversation (e.g., regarding a real estate transaction), but the encryption does not legally sign every message he or she sends.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Only when both parties come to an agreement do they sign a contract with their signing keys, and only then are they legally bound by the terms of a specific document.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] After signing, the document can be sent over the encrypted link.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] If a signing key is lost or compromised, it can be revoked to mitigate any future transactions.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] If an encryption key is lost, a backup or key escrow should be utilized to continue viewing encrypted content.
[src:dkim-signing/digital-signature] Signing keys should never be backed up or escrowed unless the backup destination is securely encrypted.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Once the DMARC DNS entry is published, any receiving email server can authenticate the incoming email based on the instructions published by the domain owner within the DNS entry.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] If the email passes the authentication, it will be delivered and can be trusted.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] If the email fails the check, depending on the instructions held within the DMARC record the email could be delivered, quarantined or rejected.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] DMARC extends two existing email authentication mechanisms, Sender Policy Framework (SPF) and DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] It allows the administrative owner of a domain to publish a policy in their DNS records to specify how to check the `From:` field presented to end users and how the receiver should deal with failures, and it provides a reporting mechanism for actions performed under those policies.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] DMARC is defined in the Internet Engineering Task Force's published document RFC 9989, dated May 2026, as "Standards Track".
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] A DMARC policy allows a sender's domain to indicate that their email messages are protected by SPF and/or DKIM, and tells a receiver what to do if neither of those authentication methods passes – such as to reject the message or quarantine it.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The policy can also specify how an email receiver can report back to the sender's domain about messages that pass and/or fail.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] These policies are published in the public Domain Name System (DNS) as text TXT records.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] DMARC does not directly address whether or not an email is spam or otherwise fraudulent.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Instead, DMARC can require that a message not only pass DKIM or SPF validation, but that it also pass § Alignment.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Under DMARC a message can fail even if it passes SPF or DKIM but fails alignment.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Setting up DMARC may improve the deliverability of messages from legitimate senders.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] DMARC operates by checking that the domain in the message's `From:` field (also called "RFC5322.From") is "aligned" with other authenticated domain names.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] If either SPF (specified using the `aspf` field) or DKIM (specified using the `adkim` field) alignment checks pass, then the DMARC alignment test passes.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Alignment may be specified as strict or relaxed.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] For strict alignment, the domain names must be identical.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] For relaxed alignment, the top-level "Organizational Domain" must match.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The Organizational Domain used to be found by checking a list of public DNS suffixes.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The upcoming spec instead specifies a Tree Walk through the parent domains.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] So, for example, "a.b.c.d.example.com.au" and "example.com.au" have the same Organizational Domain, because _dmarc.example.com.au is the only defined DMARC record among all the subdomains involved, including _dmarc.au.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] As this allows domain owners to define domain roles, it is deemed to be more accurate than the Public Suffix List.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Like SPF and DKIM, DMARC uses the concept of a domain owner, the entity or entities authorized to make changes to a given DNS domain.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] SPF checks that the IP address of the sending server is authorized by the owner of the domain that appears in the SMTP `MAIL FROM` command.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] (The email address in MAIL FROM is also called the bounce address, envelope-from or RFC5321.MailFrom.) In addition to requiring that the SPF check passes, DMARC checks that RFC5321.MailFrom aligns with 5322.From.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] DKIM allows parts of an email message to be cryptographically signed, and the signature must cover the From field.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Within the DKIM-Signature mail header, the `d=` (domain) and `s=` (selector) tags specify where in DNS to retrieve the public key for the signature.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] A valid signature proves that the signer is a domain owner, and that the From field hasn't been modified since the signature was applied.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] There may be several DKIM signatures on an email message; DMARC requires one valid signature where the domain in the `d=` tag aligns with the sender's domain stated in the `From:` header field.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] DMARC records are published in DNS with a subdomain label `_dmarc`, for example `_dmarc.example.com`.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Compare this to SPF at `example.com`, and DKIM at `selector._domainkey.example.com`.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The content of the TXT resource record consists of `name=value` tags, separated by semicolons, similar to SPF and DKIM.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] In this example, the entity controlling the example.com DNS domain intends to monitor SPF and/or DKIM failure rates and doesn't expect email to be sent from subdomains of example.com.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Note that a subdomain can publish its own DMARC record; receivers must check it out before falling back to the organizational domain record.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The protocol provides for various ratchets, or transitional states, to allow mail admins to gradually transition from not implementing DMARC at all, all the way through to an unyielding setup.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The concept of stepwise adoption assumes that the goal of DMARC is the strongest setting, which is not the case for all domains.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Regardless of intent, these mechanisms allow for greater flexibility.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The policy published can be mitigated by applying it to only a percentage of the messages that fail DMARC check.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Receivers are asked to select the given percentage of messages by a simple Bernoulli sampling algorithm.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The rest of the messages should undergo the lower policy; that is, none if `p=quarantine`, quarantine if `p=reject`.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] If not specified, pct defaults to 100% of messages.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The case `p=quarantine; pct=0;` is being used to force mailing list managers to rewrite the From: field, as some don't do so when `p=none`.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Finally, the subdomain policy, `sp=` and the newly added no-domain policy, `np=` allow tweaking the policy for specific subdomains.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] DMARC is capable of producing two separate types of reports.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Aggregate reports are sent to the address specified following the `rua`.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Forensic reports are emailed to the address following the `ruf` tag.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] These mail addresses must be specified in URI mailto format (e.g. mailto:worker@example.net ).
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Multiple reporting addresses are valid and must each be in full URI format, separated by a comma.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Target email addresses can belong to external domains.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] In that case, the target domain has to set up a DMARC record to say it agrees to receive them, otherwise it would be possible to exploit reporting for spam amplification.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] For example, say `receiver.example` receives a mail message `From: someone@sender.example` and wishes to report it.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Aggregate Reports are sent as XML files, typically once per day.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The subject mentions the "Report Domain", which indicates the DNS domain name about which the report was generated, and the "Submitter", which is the entity issuing the report.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The XML content consists of a header, containing the policy on which the report is based and report metadata, followed by a number of records.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Records can be put in a database as a relation and viewed in a tabular form.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The XML schema is defined in Appendix C of specifications and a raw record is exemplified in dmarc.org.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Here we stick with a relational example, which better conveys the nature of the data.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] DMARC records can also be directly transformed in HTML by applying an XSL stylesheet.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Rows are grouped by source IP and authentication results, passing just the count of each group.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The leftmost result columns, labelled **SPF** and **DKIM** show DMARC-wise results, either pass or fail, taking alignment into account.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The rightmost ones, with similar labels, show the name of the domain which claims to participate in the sending of the message and (in parentheses) the authentication status of that claim according to the original protocol, SPF or DKIM, regardless of Identifier Alignment.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] On the right side, SPF can appear at most twice, once for the `Return-Path:` test and once for the `HELO` test; DKIM can appear once for each signature present in the message.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] In the example, the first row represents the main mail flow from example.org, and the second row is a DKIM glitch, such as signature breakage due to a minor alteration in transit.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The third and fourth rows show typical failures modes of a forwarder and a mailing list, respectively.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] DMARC authentication failed for the last row only; it could have affected the message disposition if example.org had specified a strict policy.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The **disposition** reflects the policy published actually applied to the messages, *none*, *quarantine*, or *reject*.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Along with it, not shown in the table, DMARC provides for a policy override.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] if none of the above applies, a comment field allows to say more.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Failure Reports, also known as Forensic Reports, are generated in real time and consist of possibly redacted copies of individual messages that failed SPF, DKIM or both based upon what value is specified in the `fo` tag.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Their format, an extension of Abuse Reporting Format, resembles that of regular bounces in that they contain either a "message/rfc822" or a "text/rfc822-headers".
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] There are several different types of email forwarding, some of which may break SPF.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] This is one of the reasons why email forwarding can affect DMARC authentication results.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Mailing lists are a frequent cause of legitimate breakage of the original author's domain DKIM signature, for example by adding a prefix to the subject header.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] A number of workarounds are possible, and mailing list software packages are working on solutions.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] This workaround keeps the standard mailing list workflow, and is adopted by several large mailing list operators, but precludes the list adding footers and subject prefixes.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] This requires careful configuration of mailing software to make sure signed headers are not reordered or modified.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] A misconfigured email server may put List-id in its DKIM of messages sent to a mailing list, and then the list operator is forced to reject it or do From: rewriting.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] One of the most popular and least intrusive workarounds consists of rewriting the `From:` header field.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The original author's address can then be added to the `Reply-To:` field.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Rewriting can range from just appending `.INVALID` to the domain name, to allocating a temporary user ID where a modified version of the user's address is used, or an opaque ID is used, which keeps the user's "real" email address private from the list.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] In addition, the display name can be changed so as to show both the author and the list (or list operator).
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The last line, `Reply-To:`, has to be designed in order to accommodate reply-to-author functionality, in which case reply-to-list functionality is covered by the preceding change in the `From:` header field.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] That way, the original meaning of those fields is reversed.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Altering the author is not fair in general, and can break the expected relationship between meaning and appearance of that datum.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] There are communities which use mailing lists to coordinate their work, and deploy tools which use the `From:` field to attribute authorship to attachments.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Wrapping the message works nicely, for those who use an email client which understands wrapped messages.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Not doing any change is perhaps the most obvious solution, except that they seem to be legally required in some countries, and that routinely losing SPF authentication may render overall authentication more fragile.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The `Sender:` header is available to indicate that an email was sent on behalf of another party, but DMARC only checks policy for the From domain and ignores the Sender domain.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Both ADSP and DMARC reject using the Sender field on the non-technical basis that many user agents do not display this to the recipient.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] A draft DMARC specification has been maintained since 30 January 2012.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] In October 2013, GNU Mailman 2.1.16 was released with options to handle posters from a domain with the DMARC policy of `p=reject`.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] The change tried to anticipate the interoperability issues expected in case restrictive policies were applied to domains with human users (as opposed to purely transactional mail domains).
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] In April 2014, Yahoo changed its DMARC policy to `p=reject`, thereby causing misbehavior in several mailing lists.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] A few days later, AOL also changed its DMARC policy to `p=reject`.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Those moves resulted in a significant amount of disruption, and those mailbox providers have been accused of forcing the costs of their own security failures onto third parties.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] As of 2020, the FAQ in the official DMARC wiki contains several suggestions for mailing lists to handle messages from a domain with a strict DMARC policy, of which the most widely implemented is the mailing list changing the “From” header to an address in its own domain.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] An IETF working group was formed in August 2014 in order to address DMARC issues, starting from interoperability concerns and possibly continuing with a revised standard specification and documentation.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Meanwhile, the existing DMARC specification had reached an editorial state agreed upon and implemented by many.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] It was published in March 2015 on the Independent Submission stream in the "Informational" (non-standard) category as RFC 7489.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] In March 2017, the Federal Trade Commission published a study on DMARC usage by businesses.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Out of 569 businesses, the study found about a third implemented any DMARC configuration, fewer than 10% used DMARC to instruct servers to reject unauthenticated messages, and a majority had implemented SPF.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] An updated RFC 9989 was published in May 2026.
[src:dkim-signing/dmarc] Popular services that perform DMARC analysis and/or record validation include Red Sift, Valimail, dmarcian, DMARC Advisor and EasyDmarc and Cloudflare.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The receiver can check that an email that claimed to have come from a specific domain was indeed authorized by the owner of that domain.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] It achieves this by affixing a digital signature, linked to a domain name, to each outgoing email message.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The recipient system can verify this by looking up the sender's public key published in the DNS.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] A valid signature also guarantees that some parts of the email (possibly including attachments) have not been modified since the signature was affixed.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Usually, DKIM signatures are not visible to end-users, and are affixed or verified by the infrastructure rather than the message's authors and recipients.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] It is defined in RFC 6376, dated September 2011, with updates in RFC 8301, RFC 8463, RFC 8553, and RFC 8616.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The need for email validated identification arises because forged addresses and content are otherwise easily created—and widely used in spam, phishing and other email-based fraud.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] For example, a fraudster may send a message claiming to be from *sender@example.com*, with the goal of convincing the recipient to accept and to read the email—and it is difficult for recipients to establish whether to trust this message.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] System administrators also have to deal with complaints about malicious emails that appear to have originated from their systems, but did not.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM provides the ability to sign a message, and allows the signer (*author* organization) to communicate which email it considers legitimate.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] It does not directly prevent or disclose abusive behavior.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM also provides a process for verifying a signed message.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Verifying modules typically act on behalf of the *receiver* organization, possibly at each hop.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] All of this is independent of Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) routing aspects, in that it operates on the RFC 5322 message—the transported mail's header and body—not the SMTP "envelope" defined in RFC 5321.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Hence, DKIM signatures survive basic relaying across multiple message transfer agents.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The signing organization can be a direct handler of the message, such as the author, mail submission agent, site, or further intermediary along the transit path, or an indirect handler such as an independent service that is providing assistance to a direct handler.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Signing modules insert one or more `DKIM-Signature:` header fields, possibly on behalf of the *author* organization or the originating service provider.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The specification allows signers to choose which header fields they sign, but the `From:` field must always be signed.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The most relevant ones are **b** for the actual digital signature of the contents (headers and body) of the mail message, **bh** for the body hash (optionally limited to the first **l** octets of the body), **d** for the signing domain, and **s** for the selector.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] An Agent or User Identifier (AUID) can optionally be included.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The format is an email address with an optional local-part.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The domain must be equal to, or a subdomain of, the signing domain.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The semantics of the AUID are intentionally left undefined, and may be used by the signing domain to establish a more fine-grained sphere of responsibility.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Both header and body contribute to the signature.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] First, the message body is hashed, always from the beginning, possibly truncated to a given length **l** (which may be zero).
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Second, selected header fields are hashed, in the order given by **h**.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Repeated field names are matched from the bottom of the header upward, which is the order in which `Received:` fields are inserted in the header.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] A non-existing field matches the empty string, so that adding a field with that name will break the signature.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The `DKIM-Signature:` field of the signature being created, with **bh** equal to the computed body hash and **b** equal to the empty string, is implicitly added to the second hash, albeit its name must not appear in **h** — if it does, it refers to another, preexisting signature.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] For both hashes, text is canonicalized according to the relevant **c** algorithms.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The result, after encryption with the signer's private key and encoding using Base64, is **b**.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In addition to the list of header fields listed in **h**, a list of header fields (including both field name and value) present at the time of signing may be provided in **z**.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] This list need not match the list of headers in **h**.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Algorithms, fields, and body length are meant to be chosen so as to assure unambiguous message identification while still allowing signatures to survive the unavoidable changes which are going to occur in transit.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] No end-to-end data integrity is implied.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] A receiving SMTP server wanting to verify uses the domain name and the selector to perform a DNS lookup.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] For example, given the example signature above: the **d** tag gives the *author* domain to be verified against, *example.net* ; the **s** tag the selector, *brisbane*.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The string *_domainkey* is a fixed part of the specification.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Note that the selector and the domain name can be UTF-8 in internationalized email.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In that case the label must be encoded according to IDNA before lookup.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The data returned from the query of this record is also a list of tag-value pairs.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] A CNAME record can also be used to point at a different TXT record, for example when one organization sends email on behalf of another.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The receiver can use the public key (value of the **p** tag) to then validate the signature on the hash value in the header field, and check it against the hash value for the mail message (headers and body) that was received.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] If the two values match, this cryptographically proves that the mail was signed by the indicated domain and has not been tampered with in transit.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Signature verification failure does not force rejection of the message.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Instead, the precise reasons why the authenticity of the message could not be proven should be made available to downstream and upstream processes.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Methods for doing so may include sending back an FBL message, or adding an `Authentication-Results:` header field to the message as described in RFC 7001.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DomainKeys was covered by U.S. patent 6,986,049, now expired.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Yahoo! licensed its patent claims under a dual license scheme: the *DomainKeys Patent License Agreement v1.2*, or *GNU General Public License v2.0 (and no other version)*.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In essence, both DKIM and SPF provide different measures of email authenticity.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The primary advantage of this system for e-mail recipients is in allowing the signing domain to reliably identify a stream of legitimate email, thereby allowing domain-based blacklists and whitelists to be more effective.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] This is also likely to make certain kinds of phishing attacks easier to detect.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM is a method of labeling a message, and it does not itself filter or identify spam.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, widespread use of DKIM can prevent spammers from forging the source address of their messages, a technique they commonly employ today.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] If spammers are forced to show a correct source domain, other filtering techniques can work more effectively.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In particular, the source domain can feed into a reputation system to better identify spam.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Conversely, DKIM can make it easier to identify mail that is known not to be spam and need not be filtered.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] If a receiving system has a whitelist of known good sending domains, either locally maintained or from third party certifiers, it can skip the filtering on signed mail from those domains, and perhaps filter the remaining mail more aggressively.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM can be useful as an anti-phishing technology.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Mailers in heavily phished domains can sign their mail to show that it is genuine.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Recipients can take the absence of a valid signature on mail from those domains to be an indication that the mail is probably forged.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The best way to determine the set of domains that merit this degree of scrutiny remains an open question.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM used to have an optional feature called ADSP that lets authors that sign all their mail self-identify, but it was demoted to historic status in November 2013.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Instead, DMARC can be used for the same purpose and allows domains to self-publish which techniques (including SPF and DKIM) they employ, which makes it easier for the receiver to make an informed decision whether a certain mail is spam or not.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] For example, using DMARC, eBay and PayPal both publish policies that all of their mail is authenticated, and requesting that any receiving system, such as Gmail, should reject any that is not.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Because it is implemented using DNS records and an added RFC 5322 header field, DKIM is compatible with the existing e-mail infrastructure.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In particular, it is transparent to existing e-mail systems that lack DKIM support.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] This design approach also is compatible with other, related services, such as the S/MIME and OpenPGP content-protection standards.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM is compatible with the DNSSEC standard and with SPF.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM requires cryptographic checksums to be generated for each message sent through a mail server, which results in computational overhead not otherwise required for e-mail delivery.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] This additional computational overhead is a hallmark of digital postmarks, making sending bulk spam more (computationally) expensive.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] This facet of DKIM may look similar to hashcash, except that the receiver side verification is a negligible amount of work, while a typical hashcash algorithm would require far more work.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM's non-repudiation feature prevents senders (such as spammers) from credibly denying having sent an email.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] It has proven useful to news media sources such as WikiLeaks, which has been able to leverage DKIM body signatures to prove that leaked emails were genuine and not tampered with.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In practice, it is hard to verify many old emails due to key rotation and difficulty in finding the original keys before rotation, as they are not published anywhere.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] One way to verify old emails is to use archives that collect signatures and selectors from existing emails, and can recover expired public keys from pairs of signatures done by the same key.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Green considers non-repudiation a non-wanted feature of DKIM, forced by behaviors such as those just described.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Indeed, DKIM protocol provides for expiration.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] There is an optional **x** tag on each signature, which establishes a formal expiration time; however, verifiers can ignore it.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In addition, domain owners can revoke a public key by removing its cryptographic data from the record, thereby preventing signature verification unless someone saved the public key data beforehand.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM key rotation is often recommended just to minimize the impact of compromised keys.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, in order to definitely disable non-repudiation, expired secret keys can be published, thereby allowing everyone to produce fake signatures, thus voiding the significance of original ones.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] By default, publishing a redacted email is not verifiable because the DKIM body hashes cannot be constructed.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, you can still verify such emails if the owner creates a zero-knowledge proof of the DKIM signature on a masked subset of headers or body text, while constraining the disclosed portions match the signed message.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Implementations often use regex or masking to hide or show selected content.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] This proof can be provided instead of a DKIM signature to third parties in order for anyone to verify the validity of the email.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] These proofs can even be generated locally on a user's device, so that the redacted information is never sent to third parties.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] It can be used to create secure anonymous message boards with private identities but verified affiliations, like a fully private Blind.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] It can also be used when authenticating a sender's claim is needed, but the recipient wants to remain anonymous.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The RFC itself identifies a number of potential attack vectors.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM signatures do not encompass the message envelope, which holds the return-path and message recipients.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Since DKIM does not attempt to protect against mis-addressing, this does not affect its utility.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] A number of concerns were raised and refuted in 2013 at the time of the standardization.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] A concern for any cryptographic solution would be message replay abuse, which bypasses techniques that currently limit the level of abuse from larger domains.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Replay can be inferred by using per-message public keys, tracking the DNS queries for those keys and filtering out the high number of queries due to e-mail being sent to large mailing lists or malicious queries by bad actors.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] For a comparison of different methods also addressing this problem see e-mail authentication.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] As mentioned above, authentication is not the same as abuse prevention.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] A malicious email user of a reputable domain can compose a bad message and have it DKIM-signed and sent from that domain to any mailbox from where they can retrieve it as a file, so as to obtain a signed copy of the message.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Use of the **l** tag in signatures makes doctoring such messages even easier.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The signed copy can then be forwarded to a million recipients, for example through a botnet, without control.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The email provider who signed the message can block the offending user, but cannot stop the diffusion of already-signed messages.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The validity of signatures in such messages can be limited by always including an expiration time tag in signatures, or by revoking a public key periodically or upon a notification of an incident.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Effectiveness of the scenario can hardly be limited by filtering outgoing mail, as that implies the ability to detect if a message might potentially be useful to spammers.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM currently features two canonicalization algorithms, simple and relaxed, neither of which is MIME-aware.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Mail servers can legitimately convert to a different character set, and often document this with `X-MIME-Autoconverted:` header fields.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In addition, servers in certain circumstances have to rewrite the MIME structure, thereby altering the *preamble*, the *epilogue*, and entity boundaries, any of which breaks DKIM signatures.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Only plain text messages written in us-ascii, provided that MIME header fields are not signed, enjoy the robustness that end-to-end integrity requires.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The OpenDKIM Project organized a data collection involving 21 mail servers and millions of messages.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] 92.3% of observed signatures were successfully verified, a success rate that drops slightly (90.5%) when only mailing list traffic is considered.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The problems might be exacerbated when filtering or relaying software makes changes to a message.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Without specific precaution implemented by the sender, the footer addition operated by most mailing lists and many central antivirus solutions will break the DKIM signature.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] A possible mitigation is to sign only designated number of bytes of the message body.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] It is indicated by **l** tag in **DKIM-Signature** header.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Anything added beyond the specified length of the message body is not taken into account while calculating DKIM signature.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Another workaround is to whitelist known forwarders; e.g., by SPF.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] For yet another workaround, it was proposed that forwarders verify the signature, modify the email, and then re-sign the message with a Sender: header.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, this solution has its risk with forwarded third party signed messages received at SMTP receivers supporting the RFC 5617 ADSP protocol.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Thus, in practice, the receiving server still has to whitelist known *message streams*.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The Authenticated Received Chain (ARC) is an email authentication system designed to allow an intermediate mail server like a mailing list or forwarding service to sign an email's original authentication results.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] This allows a receiving service to validate an email when the email's SPF and DKIM records are rendered invalid by an intermediate server's processing.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] ARC is defined in RFC 8617, published in July 2019, as "Experimental".
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In October 2012, *Wired* reported that mathematician Zach Harris detected and demonstrated an email source spoofing vulnerability with short DKIM keys for the `google.com` corporate domain, as well as several other high-profile domains.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] He stated that authentication with 384-bit keys can be factored in as little as 24 hours "on my laptop," and 512-bit keys, in about 72 hours with cloud computing resources.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Harris found that many organizations sign email with such short keys; he factored them all and notified the organizations of the vulnerability.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] He states that 768-bit keys could be factored with access to very large amounts of computing power, so he suggests that DKIM signing should use key lengths greater than 1,024.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM resulted in 2004 from merging two similar efforts, "enhanced DomainKeys" from Yahoo and "Identified Internet Mail" from Cisco.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] This merged specification has been the basis for a series of IETF standards-track specifications and support documents which eventually resulted in STD 76, currently RFC 6376.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] "Identified Internet Mail" was proposed by Cisco as a signature-based mail authentication standard, while DomainKeys was designed by Yahoo to verify the DNS domain of an e-mail sender and the message integrity.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Aspects of DomainKeys, along with parts of Identified Internet Mail, were combined to create DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Trendsetting providers implementing DKIM include Yahoo, Gmail, AOL and FastMail.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Any mail from these organizations should carry a DKIM signature.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Discussions about DKIM signatures passing through indirect mail flows, formally in the DMARC working group, took place right after the first adoptions of the new protocol wreaked havoc on regular mailing list use.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, none of the proposed DKIM changes passed.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Instead, mailing list software was changed.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In 2017, another working group was launched, DKIM Crypto Update (dcrup), with the specific restriction to review signing techniques.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] It adds an elliptic curve algorithm to the existing RSA.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The added key type, `k=ed25519` is adequately strong while featuring short public keys, more easily publishable in DNS.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] The original *DomainKeys* was designed by Mark Delany of Yahoo! and enhanced through comments from many others since 2004.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] It is specified in Historic RFC 4870, superseded by Standards Track RFC 4871, DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM) Signatures; both published in May 2007.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] A number of clarifications and conceptualizations were collected thereafter and specified in RFC 5672, August 2009, in the form of corrections to the existing specification.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In September 2011, RFC 6376 merged and updated the latter two documents, while preserving the substance of the DKIM protocol.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Public key compatibility with the earlier DomainKeys is also possible.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Source code development of one common library is led by *The OpenDKIM Project*, following the most recent protocol additions, and licensing under the New BSD License.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Email providers are increasingly requiring senders to implement email authentication in order to successfully deliver mail to their users' mailboxes.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] In February 2024, Google started requiring bulk senders to authenticate their emails with DKIM to successfully deliver emails to Google-hosted mailboxes.
[src:dkim-signing/domainkeys-identified-mail] Similarly in February 2024, Yahoo started requiring bulk senders to implement SPF and DKIM to successfully deliver emails to Yahoo users.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The original base of Internet email, Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP), has no such feature, so forged sender addresses in emails (a practice known as email spoofing) have been widely used in phishing, email spam, and various types of frauds.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] To combat this, many competing email authentication proposals have been developed.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] By 2018 three had been widely adopted – SPF, DKIM and DMARC.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The results of such validation can be used in automated email filtering, or can assist recipients when selecting an appropriate action.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] This article does not cover user authentication of email submission and retrieval.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] In the early 1980s, when Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) was designed, it provided for no real verification of sending user or system.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] This was not a problem while email systems were run by trusted corporations and universities, but since the commercialization of the Internet in the early 1990s, spam, phishing, and other crimes have been found to increasingly involve email.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Email authentication is a necessary first step towards identifying the origin of messages, and thereby making policies and laws more enforceable.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Hinging on domain ownership is a stance that emerged in the early 2000.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] It implies a coarse-grained authentication, given that domains appear on the right part of email addresses, after the at sign.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Fine-grained authentication, at a user level, can be achieved by other means, such as Pretty Good Privacy and S/MIME.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] At present, each individual must ultimately manage their own digital identity.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] An outstanding rationale for email authentication is the ability to automate email filtering at receiving servers.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] That way, spoofed messages can be rejected before they arrive to a user's inbox.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] While protocols strive to devise ways to reliably block distrusted mail, security indicators can tag unauthenticated messages that still reach the inbox.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A 2018 study shows that security indicators can lower the click-through ratio by more than ten points: 48.9% to 37.2% of the users who open spoofed messages.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] SMTP defines message *transport*, not the message *content*.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Thus, it defines the mail *envelope* and its parameters, such as the envelope sender, but not the header (except *trace information*) nor the body of the message itself.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] STD 10 and RFC 5321 define SMTP (the envelope), while STD 11 and RFC 5322 define the message (header and body), formally referred to as the Internet Message Format.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A mail user agent (MUA) knows the *outgoing mail* SMTP server from its configuration.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] An MTA (or a relay server) typically determines which server to connect to by looking up the MX (Mail eXchange) DNS resource record for each recipient's domain name.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The first few lines at the top of the header are usually trusted by the recipient.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Those lines are written by machines in the recipient's Administrative Management Domain (ADMD), which act upon their explicit mandate.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] By contrast, the lines that prove the involvement of **A** and **B**, as well as of the purported author's MUA could be a counterfeit created by **C**.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The `Received:` field shown above is an epoch-making piece of the header.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The `Return-Path:` is written by **E**, the mail delivery agent (MDA), based on the message *envelope*.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Additional trace fields, designed for email authentication, can populate the top of the header.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Normally, messages sent out by an author's ADMD go directly to the destination's MX (that is **B → D** in the figures).
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The sender's ADMD can add authentication tokens only if the message goes through its boxes.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Properly configured proxies appear as part of the author ADMD.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Some ADMDs block outbound connection to port 25 (SMTP) to avoid this.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] This proactive technique is described in RFC 5068.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] In addition, some block inbound SMTP connections from IPs listed as dialup/DSL/cable.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] In this case the author's ADMD is not involved at all.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Some ISPs block port 587, although RFC 5068 clearly says: Access Providers MUST NOT block users from accessing the external Internet using the SUBMISSION port 587.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] SPF allows the receiver to check that an email claimed to have come from a specific domain comes from an IP address authorized by that domain's administrators.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Usually, a domain administrator will authorize the IP addresses used by their own outbound MTAs, including any proxy or smarthost.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The IP address of the sending MTA is guaranteed to be valid by the Transmission Control Protocol, as it establishes the connection by checking that the remote host is reachable.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The receiving mail server receives the `HELO` SMTP command soon after the connection is set up, and a `Mail from:` at the beginning of each message.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The SPF verifier queries the Domain Name System (DNS) for a matching SPF record, which if it exists will specify the IP addresses authorized by that domain's administrator.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The result can be "pass", "fail", or some intermediate result - and systems will generally take this into account in their anti-spam filtering.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] DKIM checks the *message content*, deploying digital signatures.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Rather than using digital certificates, the keys for signature-verification are distributed via the DNS.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] That way, a message gets associated to a domain name.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A DKIM-compliant domain administrator generates one or more pairs of asymmetric keys, then hands private keys to the signing MTA, and publishes public keys on the DNS.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The DNS labels are structured as `*selector*._domainkey.example.com`, where *selector* identifies the key pair, and `_domainkey` is a fixed keyword, followed by the signing domain's name so that publication occurs under the authority of that domain's ADMD.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Just before injecting a message into the SMTP transport system, the signing MTA creates a digital signature that covers selected fields of the header and the body (or just its beginning).
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The signature should cover substantive header fields such as `From:`, `To:`, `Date:`, and `Subject:`, and then is added to the message header itself, as a trace field.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Any number of relays can receive and forward the message and at every hop, the signature can be verified by retrieving the public key from the DNS.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] As long as intermediate relays do not modify signed parts of a message, its DKIM-signatures remain valid.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] DMARC allows the specification of a policy for authenticated messages.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] It is built on top of two existing mechanisms, Sender Policy Framework (SPF) and DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A range of other methods have been proposed, but are now either deprecated or have not yet gained widespread support.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] ADSP allowed the specification of a policy for messages signed by the author's domain.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A message had to go through DKIM authentication first, then ADSP could demand a punishing treatment if the message was not signed by the author domain(s) —as per the `From:` header field.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] ADSP was demoted to historic in November 2013.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] VBR adds a vouch to an already authenticated identity.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] This method requires some globally recognized authorities that certify the reputation of domains.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A sender can apply for a reference at a vouching authority.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The reference, if accepted, is published on the DNS branch managed by that authority.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A vouched sender should add a `VBR-Info:` header field to the messages it sends.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] It should also add a DKIM signature, or use some other authentication method, such as SPF.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A receiver, after validating the sender's identity, can verify the vouch claimed in `VBR-Info:` by looking up the reference.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Applications should avoid using this method as a means of authentication.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Nevertheless, it is often carried out and its results, if any, written in the `Received:` header field besides the TCP information required by the SMTP specification.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The IP reverse, confirmed by looking up the IP address of the name just found, is just an indication that the IP was set up properly in the DNS.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The reverse resolution of a range of IP addresses can be delegated to the ADMD that uses them, or can remain managed by the network provider.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] In the latter case, no useful identity related to the message can be obtained.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Looking up a DNSWL (DNS-based whitelist) may provide an assessment of the sender, possibly including its identification.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] RFC 8601 defines a trace header field `Authentication-Results:` where a receiver can record the results of email authentication checks that it carried out.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Multiple results for multiple *methods* can be reported in the same field, separated by semicolons and wrapped as appropriate.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The first token after the field name, `receiver.example.org`, is the ID of the authentication server, a token known as an *authserv-id*.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A receiver supporting RFC 8601 is responsible to remove (or rename) any false header claiming to belong to its domain so that downstream filters cannot get confused.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] However, those filters still need to be configured, as they have to know which identities the domain may use.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] For a Mail User Agent (MUA), it is slightly harder to learn what identities it can trust.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Since users can receive email from multiple domains—e.g., if they have multiple email addresses -— any of those domains could let `Authentication-Results:` fields pass through because they looked neutral.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] That way, a malicious sender can forge an *authserv-id* that the user would trust if the message arrived from a different domain.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] A legitimate `Authentication-Results:` typically appears just above a `Received:` field by the same domain from which the message was relayed.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Additional `Received:` fields may appear between that and the top of the header, as the message got transferred internally between servers belonging to that same, trusted ADMD.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority maintains a registry of Email Authentication Parameters.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] Not all parameters need to be registered, though.
[src:dkim-signing/email-authentication] For example, there can be local "policy" values designed for a site's internal use only, which correspond to local configuration and need no registration.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:dkim-signing/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
